Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["1 - Executive Summary", "Section",
 PageBreakAbove->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.694341537930465*^9, 3.694341550254487*^9}, {
   3.694342355079833*^9, 3.694342363410248*^9}, 3.6943428651189747`*^9, {
   3.6943430193857985`*^9, 3.694343019923829*^9}, {3.9912999869728966`*^9, 
   3.991299987150076*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c84ad9d9-f16d-4ebd-becc-\
c5897e98c089"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This report addresses the ",
 StyleBox["\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Tetrahedron Problem : finding the four \
triangular face areas of a tetrahedron whose total surface area is 18 units, \
each area being a natural number.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n \nWe model a trirectangular tetrahedron, whose three faces meeting at \
the right-angled vertex have areas xy/2, xz/2 and yz/2, while the fourth face \
obeys De Gua\[CloseCurlyQuote]s theorem A4^2 = A1^2 + A2^2 + A3^2.\n\n\
Minimizing the quality function to zero enforces the total-area target S, and \
we evaluate this systematically for every integer target from S = 4 to S = \
100. For the required total S = 18, the search returns a single solution (up \
to permutation): the face areas (2, 3, 6, 7), with edges x = Sqrt(2), y = 2 \
Sqrt(2), z = 3 Sqrt(2). \n\nAll computations and visualizations were carried \
out in Wolfram Mathematica.\n"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->CompressedData["
1:eJxTTMoPSmViYGAQBmIQ/Yizauoc69eO+48HTwfRRb23orhtXzvWJDlHg2ju
4zvTQfTu+1szQHTKr6tVINoq6y+Ybik6viO17bXjI8/Zu0H0/M/TeNKA9Lzz
78D0fbWt4iA6YPUjCRDtp9uhBKJPT1ypDKI3VXRogmim3ilaYPnkDwZg9XM4
jEF0mMMLMxCtpbPQAkRX1Ry0A9GqXnt9QfSlWqEYEF2hPj8WRN/Qk2a6aPLW
cc8VLTCtUKr+9+yet44l788JnwPSe6T1pED0lVsm0iC6Zb59BYg+MecGmNbw
/tcLolnqRPtAdIDF6V8gek4E628QDQAe3Zuj
  "],ExpressionUUID->"cb0726f4-594f-43e4-8e77-5d99a6d9f22b"]
}, Open  ]],

